To make the background cover the entire page without any margins or paddings, you can add the following CSS to the body element:
```css
body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  background-color: #e8e8e8;
  font-family: 'DM Sans',sans-serif;
  text-align: center;
  /* Add these lines */
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
}
```
This will set the position of the body to be absolute and fill the entire viewport, effectively removing any margins or paddings. The `top`, `left`, `right`, and `bottom` properties set the position of the body to be at the edges of the viewport. The `position` property needs to be set to `absolute` to allow the `top`, `left`, `right`, and `bottom` properties to work.

To add icons to each side of the messages in the dialog, you can use CSS pseudo-elements `:before` and `:after` along with the `content` property. Here is an example code snippet:
```css
/* Sender message */
.sender {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  text-align: left;
  position: relative; /* add this to position the pseudo-element */
}
.sender .message {
  background-color: rgb(2, 205, 143, 0.6);
  color: black;
  padding: 10px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 70%;
  font-size: 14px;
  position: relative; /* add this to position the pseudo-element */
}

/* Add this for the sender's icon */
.sender .message:before {
  content: '';
  display: inline-block;
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  background-image: url('path/to/sender-icon.png');
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-size: cover;
  position: absolute;
  left: -30px;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
}

/* Receiver message */
.receiver {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  text-align: right;
  position: relative; /* add this to position the pseudo-element */
}
.receiver .message {
  background-color: #E0E0E0;
  color: black;
  padding: 10px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 70%;
  font-size: 14px;
  position: relative; /* add this to position the pseudo-element */
}

/* Add this for the receiver's icon */
.receiver .message:after {
  content: '';
  display: inline-block;
  width: 20px;
  height: 20px;
  background-image: url('path/to/receiver-icon.png');
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-size: cover;
  position: absolute;
  right: -30px;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
}
```
Note that you will need to replace `path/to/sender-icon.png` and `path/to/receiver-icon.png` with the actual file paths of the sender and receiver icons, respectively. Also, adjust the `width` and `height` values of the icons to match the actual size of your icons.

To make the background appear infinite on the bottom, you can use a background image that has a repeating pattern. Here's an example:

1. Create a background image with a repeating pattern. You can use an image editor like Photoshop or GIMP to create the pattern. Save the image as a PNG, GIF or JPG.
2. Add the background image to the CSS of your HTML document using the `background-image` property. Set the `background-repeat` property to `repeat` so that the image is repeated both horizontally and vertically.
3. Set the height of the body to `100%` so that it covers the entire height of the viewport.

Here's an example code snippet:
```css
body {
  background-image: url("pattern.png");
  background-repeat: repeat;
  height: 100%;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```
In this example, the `background-image` property points to the image file `pattern.png`, which has a repeating pattern. The `background-repeat` property is set to `repeat` to repeat the image both horizontally and vertically. Finally, the `height` property is set to `100%` to cover the entire height of the viewport.

Yes, it's possible to achieve an infinite background effect without using an image, just by setting a background color and using CSS gradients.

Here's an example:
```css
body {
  background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #e8e8e8 0%, #e8e8e8 80%, #fff 80%, #fff 100%);
  background-size: 100% 100vh;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```
In this example, we're using a linear gradient as the background, which transitions from `#e8e8e8` to `#fff`. The `background-size` property is set to `100% 100vh` so that the gradient covers the entire width of the viewport and is repeated vertically every `100vh` (i.e., every full viewport height).

The trick to make the background appear infinite is by defining a "stop" in the gradient at `80%` of the height, where the color changes from `#e8e8e8` to `#fff`. This creates the illusion that the background color extends infinitely downward beyond the actual height of the page.

You can adjust the colors and the position of the stop to achieve the desired effect.

To make your page suitable for mobile devices, you can use responsive design techniques to ensure that the layout and styles adjust to the screen size of the device.

One approach is to use CSS media queries to define different styles for different screen sizes. For example, you can set a breakpoint at a certain width, and apply styles specifically for screens smaller than that width. Here's an example:
```css
/* General styling */
body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  background-color: #e8e8e8;
  font-family: 'DM Sans',sans-serif;
  text-align: center; /* center align the title */
}

/* Chat container */
.chat {
  width: 80%;
  max-width: 500px;
  margin: 50px auto;
  background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255, 0.9);
  padding: 20px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
}

/* Sender message */
.sender {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  text-align: left;
}

.sender .message {
  background-color: rgb(2,205,143, 0.6);
  color: black;
  padding: 10px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 70%;
  font-size: 14px; /* lower font size */
}

.sender .name {
  color: black;
  margin-right: 10px;
  font-size: 0px;
}

/* Receiver message */
.receiver {
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  text-align: right;
}

.receiver .message {
  background-color: #E0E0E0; /* replace with desired color */
  color: black;
  padding: 10px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  display: inline-block;
  max-width: 70%;
  font-size: 14px; /* lower font size */
}

.receiver .name {
  font-weight: bold;
  color: #E0E0E0;
  margin-left: 10px;
  display: none; /* remove the receiver's name */
}

/* Responsive styles for screens smaller than 600px */
@media only screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  .chat {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: none;
    margin: 20px 0;
  }

  .sender .message,
  .receiver .message {
    max-width: 100%;
  }
}
```
In this example, we've defined a media query with a maximum width of `600px`, which applies styles specifically for screens smaller than that width. We've adjusted the width and margins of the `.chat` container, and set the maximum width of the message elements to `100%` so they take up the full width of the container on smaller screens.

You can adjust the breakpoint and styles to suit your specific needs.
